summary.seg: This manuscript largely consists of a copy of the Tabula medicine, a vast compilation of medical remedies, which also includes charms and magical and alchemical recipes, all arranged in alphabetical order. According to Peter Jones, the original compilation of this work was made in an English mendicant community between 1416 and 1425, since these dates are given in the explicit of a copy of the work in London, University College, MS Lat. 11. The mendicant origin of the compiliation is suggested by the reference to various mendicant healers, including St Dominic, the Franciscan friars Robert Winstanton and William Holme. The Tabula medicine was subsequently adopted by English physicians and expanded with references to authorities in their field. As Jones notes, this manuscript contains notable references to Thomas Duncan (d. 1425, who studied medicine as a Fellow at Merton College, Oxford; and Gilbert Kymer (d. 1463), an Oxford M.D. (1423), who served as physician to Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester.

This manuscript may be an early copy of the Tabula medicine, since it contains a nativity on f. g recto that is dated to 1428. Despite additions attributed to physicians, the manuscript may have been produced in a religious or monastic context. The latter is suggested by the quotation of theologial sayings and the repeated occurence of the 'IHS' monogram in the upper margins of the manuscript's first and final pages. Unfortunately, nothing is known about the manuscript's early provenance: an ownership inscription appears to have been removed by cutting out a rectangular piece of parchment from the lower margin of f. I.

Dr Clarck Drieshen
Project Cataloguer in Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries
Cambridge University Library

msItem.title: Tabula medicine [Alphabetical handbook of medicinal simples from 'Abhominacio' to 'Vulua']
msItem.explicit: 275r Item oua perdicis iniuncta super vuluam elargant eam secundum gaddesden
msItem.note: Titles of recipes and names of medical authorities are written in the margins throughout the text, e.g.: Electuarium Rasis (f. 1v), Johannis de Arden (f. 7v), Emplastrum gerardi (f. 14v), holm (f. 15v), Aliud balsamum ffratris holm (f. 17r), [Johannes] Robrok (f. 17v), Waynflet (f. 22v), Gaddesden (f. 24r), Rogerus Castell (f. 55r), [Magister] Ferrarius (f. 78r), Pulius Castell (f. 82v), Waynflet (f. 104r), [Rogerus] Radcliffe (f. 105v), [Pulius Johannis] Sowthan (f. 106r), Pensax and Stokes (f. 113r), Ricardus de Poules, [Robertus] Waynflet (f. 121r), [ffrater Robertus] Wystantoun (f. 135r), rector de Billislay (f. 135v), Gerardus [de solo] (f. 136r), Bartholomeus in breviario (f. 145r), Johannis de Sancto Amando (f. 147r), pro pestilencia secunum medicum ducis glowcestere (f. 177r), Emplastrum quod dicitur Emanuel magister (f. 177v), Aschinden (f. 178r), Emanuel Fernandi (f. 182v), Albertus de saxonia (f. 232r), Haly (f. 233v), Symon Wellys (f. 234r), Barnardus de Gordonio (f. 236v), Johannes Ray (f. 248v).
Another copy of this text can be found in Cambridge, King's College, MS 16, ff. 1r-145r.

msItem.title: Medical recipes
msItem.note: The recipes refer to medieval physicians: Pulius pestilenciae secundum Hall. de Lichefeld (f. 275v); Lichefeld ut creditur (f. 275v); and Gilbertus Kymer (f. 276r).
The collection contains one Middle English recipe on f. 276r pro sciatica. This recipe has been fully transcribed by Lucas (2016), p. 52.

msItem.author: Bernard de Gordon
msItem.incipit: 277r Quoniam de melioribus amicis quos habere vidiar [sic: videor]
msItem.explicit: 280v cum medicinis infrigidantibus renes de vesicam que dicte sunt superius
msItem.finalRubric: 280v Explicit practica Magistri bernardi de villa Noua Cathalani

msItem.title: Medical recipe
msItem.textLang: Latin recipe with an (?) English heading
msItem.note: The recipe's heading is written with Greek capital letters and can be transliterated as 'Wert', suggesting that the recipe concerns a treatment for warts.
The recipe appears to be a later 15th-century addition to the manuscript.

msItem.explicit: 282v Nam si post queris querens inimicus haberis
msItem.note: Another copy of this poem, entitled De prudentia Medici sumentis pro labore is edited in Croke (1830), p. 46.

msItem.title: Alphabetical index of recipes in the Tabula medicine
Alphabetical list of plants in Latin and English
msItem.incipit: 286r Aaron barba aron jarus pes vituli zekesters ca. et sicc.
msItem.note: Similar lists of plant names in Latin and English can be found in Cambridge, Trinity College, MS O.9.10, ff. 1r-26v Oxford, Pembroke College, MS 2, ff. 343r-348v; and Sheffield Record Office, Jackson Collection 1302, f. 133v [incomplete].

This item contains occasional English plant names but is not recorded in Lucas (2016). Further study on this text is needed, but based on the incipit and explicit its closest match is the Sinonoma Bartholomei in Oxford, Pembroke College, MS 2.

msItem.title: Lists of diseases and ingredients for medical recipes
msItem.note: The lists contain various titles, e.g. venena vsualia, Infirmitates contagiose, and Oleum exetrie. Although it has not been included in Lucas (2016), the ingredients listed occasionally are written in Middle English, e.g.: Tyme, Strawbery, and Borage.

msItem.title: Medical poem
msItem.incipit: 298v Septem sunt cara quia bona vei quia rara / Balsamus ambra tirus caro lignum camphora muscus / Est opos succus . xilo lignum . carpo que frucons [sic: fructus]
msItem.note: The same poem is found in the Luminare maius by Giovanni Giacomo Manlio di Bosco (fl. 1490-post 1500).

msItem.title: Collection of magical and alchemical recipes
msItem.note: The collection contains a recipe for making an unbreakable and unpenetrable substance from goat's blood, vinegar and the juice of absinth; to become able to break free from any prison; to capture fish; to recover stolen goods.

msItem.title: Recipe for making gold or silver ink
msItem.rubric: 299r Ad faciendum encaustum aureum uel argenteum

msItem.title: Recipes for making oils of flowers
msItem.note: The recipes are for making Oleum de floribus and Oleum camomille.

msItem.title: Medical recipes
msItem.note: The recipes are largely written in Latin but three recipes on f. g recto feature Middle English names for ingredients (not included in Lucas (2016).
One recipe on f. 301r has been attributed to Peter Stanley (secundum Petrum de Stanley); another instruction on f. g recto refers to those born in the year 1448.

signatures.p: Leaf numbers occasionally visible in the right-hand lower corners of the of the first halves of quires.

catchwords.seg: Occasional catchwords, written in brown ink in the right-hand lower margins of the last versos of quires.

collation.note: This collation deviates from that of M.R. James (1895) in adding a parchment leaf, not accounted for in James's collation, to quire 2. It also accounts for 4 missing leaves in quire 10 which is described as a regular quire of 20 leaves by James.

layout.seg: Ruled in ink, frame only. Mainly single columns (except f. A recto which has 5 columns, ff. A recto and ff. 283r-299vwhich have 2 columns, and f. b recto which has 3 columns. 33-41 lines to the page, written below top line.

handNote.p: Copied by several hands working in a cursive script with both anglicana and secretary features.

decoNote.p: Two large (3-line) initials in red ink on f. 1r.
Manicules in brown ink throughout the manuscript.

additions.note: Modern quire numbers '1'-'18' written in the right-hand lower corners of the first rectos of quires.

binding.p: 20th-century quarter brown goatskin with marbled paper sides and vellum corner tips; the spine with five raised bands and gold-stamped with the classmark: 'Q' 'G' '12'.

Remains of the previous binding have been pasted on the inside of the lower cover , featuring three fragments of the old spine. These comprise two pieces of brown leather with blind-tooled decoration and a strip of leather with a gold-tooled title inscription: Miscellanea Medica MSS..

origin.origDate: Copied in the second quarter of the 15th century

history.acquisition: It is unknown how the manuscript was acquired by Jesus College: its armorial bookplate with the inscription: Collegium Jesu Cantabrigiense 1700 pasted on the inside of the upper cover; and its classmark 'Q G 12' is gold stamped on the spine.
